trans-unit.source: <run1>StarCraft</run1><run2> is a <hyperlink3>military science fiction</hyperlink3> <hyperlink4>real-time strategy</hyperlink4> <hyperlink5>video game</hyperlink5> developed by <hyperlink6>Blizzard Entertainment</hyperlink6></run2>. The first game of the <tags7/>StarCraft<tags8/>series<tags9/><run10> was released for <hyperlink11>Microsoft Windows</hyperlink11> on 31 March 1998.<hyperlink12>[1]</hyperlink12> With more than 11 million copies sold worldwide as of February 2009, it is one of the <hyperlink13>best-selling games</hyperlink13> for the <hyperlink14>personal computer</hyperlink14></run10>.<hyperlink15>[3]</hyperlink15><run16> A <hyperlink17>Mac OS</hyperlink17> version was released in March 1999, and a <hyperlink18>Nintendo 64</hyperlink18></run16>adaptation co-developed with <hyperlink19>Mass Media Interactive Entertainment</hyperlink19><run20> was released on 13 June 2000.<hyperlink21>[2]</hyperlink21> </run20><run22>StarCraft</run22><run23> has had its storyline adapted and expanded through a series of novels, the <hyperlink24>expansion pack</hyperlink24> <hyperlink25>StarCraft: Brood War</hyperlink25> and two authorized add-ons. The game's sequel, <hyperlink26>StarCraft II: Wings of Liberty</hyperlink26></run23>, was released in July 2010.

trans-unit.source: Set in the 26th century, the game revolves around three species fighting for dominance in a distant part of the <hyperlink1>Milky Way</hyperlink1><run2> galaxy: the<hyperlink3>Terrans</hyperlink3></run2>, humans exiled from Earth skilled at adapting to any situation; the <tags4/>Zerg<tags5/>, a race of <tags6/>insectoid<tags7/><run8> aliens in pursuit of genetic perfection, obsessed with assimilating other races; and the </run8><tags9/>Protoss<tags10/>, a <hyperlink11>humanoid</hyperlink11><run12> species with advanced technology and <hyperlink13>psionic abilities</hyperlink13></run12>, attempting to preserve their civilization and strict philosophical way of living from the Zerg. The game has been praised for pioneering the use of unique factions in real-time strategy gameplay<run14><tags15/>[4]<tags16/></run14><run17> and for a compelling story.<hyperlink18>[5]</hyperlink18></run17>

trans-unit.source: Many of the industry's journalists have praised <run1>StarCraft</run1><run2> as one of the best<hyperlink3>[6]</hyperlink3> and most important<hyperlink4>[7]</hyperlink4> video games of all time, and for having raised the bar for developing real-time strategy games.<hyperlink5>[8]</hyperlink5> </run2><run6>StarCraft</run6>'s <hyperlink7>multiplayer</hyperlink7><run8> is particularly popular in <hyperlink9>South Korea</hyperlink9></run8>, where players and teams participate in <hyperlink10>professional competitions</hyperlink10>, earn sponsorships, and compete in televised tournaments.<hyperlink11>[9]</hyperlink11>
